obo:UBERON_0002421  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:SYNGO_3007  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig.1: \"Expression of Abp1 full length and fragments thereof containing the F-actin binding domains induce increased spine length\"\n\nFig.2: \"Abp1 overexpression results predominantly in elongation of mushroom-type spines\"\n\nFig.3: \"Effects of full-length Abp1 and actin interaction domains of Abp1 on the density of mushroom-shaped spines and synapses\"\n\nFig.4: \"Overexpression of Abp1 fragments encompassing the C-terminal SH3 domain highly significantly decreases the density of mushroom spines\"\n\nFig.5: \"RNAi-based reduction of Abp1 expression levels reduces the densities of mushroom spines and synapses on hippocampal neurons\"\n\nFig.7: \"Abp1 and ProSAP1 or ProSAP2 coexpression leads to highly branched and complex spines with multiple enlarged spine heads\"\n\nDiscussion: \". Abp1 is not only able to link dynamic actin fibers to ProSAP/Shank proteins and to stabilize actin filaments (Fig. 12A,B), but it is also able to link the SH3 domain interaction partners of the WASP superfamily of Arp2/3 complex activators with F-actin and to activate N-WASP. This leads to Abp1-controlled Arp2/3 complex-mediated nucleation of actin filaments in the microenvironment of the actin- and ProSAP/Shank-rich PSD. Formation of new actin filaments then provides even more Abp1 attachment sides, because Abp1 prefers freshly polymerized actin filaments (Kessels et al., 2000). \". Experimental description: - Overexpressed Dbnl; Abp1; Sh3p7 is of mouse species (traced back to PMID:): ' pGAT2-mAbp1 \"\n- Neurons are rat: \"RNA interference (RNAi) constructs directed against rat Abp1,\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0593-3443" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2018-03-23" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_3007" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

